---
import Layout from '../../layouts/Layout.astro';
import Navbar from '../../components/Navbar.astro';
import Footer from '../../components/Footer.astro';

const heroImages = [
  { src: "https://www.figma.com/api/mcp/asset/5a155eea-c920-462e-9a33-4b3ffc18ed0d", alt: "Gallery screen 1", offset: false },
  { src: "https://www.figma.com/api/mcp/asset/645bc9d8-28b3-415f-8bfc-e5e569482127", alt: "Gallery screen 2", offset: true },
  { src: "https://www.figma.com/api/mcp/asset/382417f1-2acb-47ee-b49f-9cf942252fc8", alt: "Gallery screen 3", offset: true },
  { src: "https://www.figma.com/api/mcp/asset/60e8c291-20b8-4704-ba4f-c0d711d2fc6c", alt: "Gallery screen 4", offset: false },
];

const researchInsights = [
  "There was unexpected pop-ups when images were clicked.",
  "There was no quit (X) or back (←) icon to exit the full-screen mode.",
  "Customers often want to view specific rooms like just the bedroom or bar only.",
  "With the filter feature, users can narrow down their options.",
  "Thumbnail or grid view feature would be added in iOS app.",
  "The grid view is more efficient way to scan the entire property images.",
];

const variants = [
  {
    label: "Variant 1",
    text: "The current design is the closest to what's currently live on Expedia's mobile web, with only a few grid view modifications. I moved the description and image count to a better position. The interaction pattern remains consistent with what's seen on the mobile web version.",
  },
  {
    label: "Variant 2",
    text: "We tried to understand: Does the grid view icon work for users? Do users understand that carousel dots indicate swipe functionality? Does a two-row grid view improve the experience?",
  },
  {
    label: "Variant 3",
    text: "We tried to explore: What happens if we change the interaction to the entire grid view directly? The only access to full-screen mode is from the grid view. Is it user-friendly to compel users to tilt their phones for a larger image view? Does the mixed grid system impact the user experience? Does the picture count format (e.g., 1/25) work better than the grid icon?",
  },
];
---

<Layout title="Native Photo Gallery – Evan Luputra">
  <Navbar />

  <main class="bg-white">

    <!-- Back -->
    <div class="px-5 sm:px-10 lg:px-[120px] pt-10">
      <a href="/#projects" class="inline-flex items-center gap-2 text-sm font-medium text-primary hover:underline">
        ← Back to Projects
      </a>
    </div>

    <!-- ── HERO ── -->
    <section class="pt-10 pb-6 text-center">
      <div class="max-w-3xl mx-auto px-5 sm:px-10">
        <p class="text-sm font-semibold text-primary mb-3">Senior UX Designer @ Expedia</p>
        <h1 class="font-bold text-[36px] sm:text-[52px] lg:text-[60px] leading-tight text-[#020202] mb-5">
          Native photo gallery
        </h1>
        <p class="text-base sm:text-lg lg:text-[20px] leading-relaxed text-[#020202]">
          Redesigned the entire flow of Gallery of native photo of lodging
          (mobile app and mobile browser).
        </p>
      </div>

      <!-- 4-col staggered phone screenshots -->
      <div class="mt-10 px-5 sm:px-10 lg:px-[120px] max-w-5xl mx-auto">
        <div class="hidden sm:flex gap-4 lg:gap-6 items-start justify-center">
          {heroImages.map((img) => (
            <div class={`flex-1 rounded-[15px] overflow-hidden shadow-lg ${img.offset ? 'mt-10' : 'mt-0'}`}>
              <img src={img.src} alt={img.alt} class="w-full h-auto object-cover" loading="lazy" />
            </div>
          ))}
        </div>
        <div class="grid grid-cols-2 gap-4 sm:hidden">
          {heroImages.map((img) => (
            <div class="rounded-[15px] overflow-hidden shadow-lg">
              <img src={img.src} alt={img.alt} class="w-full h-auto object-cover" loading="lazy" />
            </div>
          ))}
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- ── UNDERSTAND THE PROBLEM ── -->
    <section class="px-5 sm:px-10 lg:px-[120px] py-16 lg:py-20">
      <div class="max-w-3xl mx-auto">
        <p class="text-primary font-bold text-[20px] mb-1">Lodging team</p>
        <h2 class="font-bold text-[24px] lg:text-[28px] text-[#020202] mb-6">Understand the problem</h2>
        <div class="space-y-4 text-[#020202] text-base lg:text-[20px] leading-relaxed">
          <p>
            Before booking a hotel via the app, we always want to view the property images. The challenging part was seeing a clear and realistic property representation. This influenced travelers' decisions on whether to finalize the booking.
          </p>
          <p>
            I worked independently as designer for this project, except for the research phase. This was one of the priority projects in Expedia, and I was given the opportunity to lead and design this from start to finish. I worked with three different Project Managers because this is such an important component and impacted many POS (Point of Sale) and share the learning with the leadership team.
          </p>
        </div>
        <div class="mt-8 p-6 bg-[#f2f2f2] rounded-2xl">
          <p class="font-bold text-[#020202] text-base lg:text-[20px] mb-2">Based on my research findings:</p>
          <p class="italic font-semibold text-[#020202] text-base lg:text-[20px] leading-relaxed">
            On average, 44–48% of travelers interacted with the Photo Grid view on the Property Detail Page (PDP).
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- ── RESEARCH FINDING (analytics) ── -->
    <section class="px-5 sm:px-10 lg:px-[120px] pb-16 lg:pb-20">
      <div class="max-w-5xl mx-auto flex flex-col sm:flex-row gap-6 items-center">
        <div class="w-full sm:w-[200px] shrink-0 rounded-2xl overflow-hidden shadow-lg">
          <img
            src="https://www.figma.com/api/mcp/asset/4e1d08e3-ad2d-4d0d-a3d3-a900c03490a6"
            alt="Expedia app – property detail page"
            class="w-full h-auto object-cover"
            loading="lazy"
          />
        </div>
        <div class="flex-1 rounded-2xl overflow-hidden shadow-lg">
          <img
            src="https://www.figma.com/api/mcp/asset/8973af43-069f-4125-a8df-0daecfe97683"
            alt="Native engagement analytics dashboard"
            class="w-full h-auto object-cover"
            loading="lazy"
          />
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- ── ANDROID APP ── -->
    <section class="px-5 sm:px-10 lg:px-[120px] py-16 lg:py-20 bg-[#f9f9f9]">
      <div class="max-w-5xl mx-auto">
        <div class="max-w-3xl mb-8">
          <p class="text-primary font-bold text-[20px] mb-1">Android App</p>
          <h2 class="font-bold text-[24px] lg:text-[28px] text-[#020202] mb-6">How did the user flow look like in Android app?</h2>
          <p class="text-base lg:text-[20px] leading-relaxed text-[#020202]">
            Users were directed to Grid/Thumbnail View after viewing the 6th image. There was no access to view the image in full-screen mode. How might we optimize the grid view? Were there particular aspects that could improve the user experience?
          </p>
        </div>
        <!-- Reuse gallery screens to illustrate Android flow -->
        <div class="flex gap-4 items-start">
          <div class="flex-1 rounded-[15px] overflow-hidden shadow-lg">
            <img src={heroImages[0].src} alt="Android – property detail page" class="w-full h-auto object-cover" loading="lazy" />
            <p class="text-xs text-center text-[#666] py-2 bg-[#f2f2f2]">Property detail page</p>
          </div>
          <div class="text-2xl text-[#aaa] self-center">→</div>
          <div class="flex-1 rounded-[15px] overflow-hidden shadow-lg mt-8">
            <img src={heroImages[1].src} alt="Android – thumbnail view" class="w-full h-auto object-cover" loading="lazy" />
            <p class="text-xs text-center text-[#666] py-2 bg-[#f2f2f2]">Thumbnail view</p>
          </div>
          <div class="text-2xl text-[#aaa] self-center">→</div>
          <div class="flex-1 rounded-[15px] overflow-hidden shadow-lg">
            <img src={heroImages[2].src} alt="Android – full gallery" class="w-full h-auto object-cover" loading="lazy" />
            <p class="text-xs text-center text-[#666] py-2 bg-[#f2f2f2]">Full gallery</p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- ── iOS APP ── -->
    <section class="px-5 sm:px-10 lg:px-[120px] py-16 lg:py-20">
      <div class="max-w-5xl mx-auto">
        <div class="max-w-3xl mb-8">
          <p class="text-primary font-bold text-[20px] mb-1">iOS App</p>
          <h2 class="font-bold text-[24px] lg:text-[28px] text-[#020202] mb-6">How was the user flow structured in the iOS app?</h2>
          <p class="text-base lg:text-[20px] leading-relaxed text-[#020202]">
            The app neither had a grid view nor a swipe feature.
          </p>
        </div>
        <div class="flex gap-4 items-start">
          <div class="flex-1 rounded-[15px] overflow-hidden shadow-lg">
            <img src={heroImages[0].src} alt="iOS – tap on the picture" class="w-full h-auto object-cover" loading="lazy" />
            <p class="text-xs text-center text-[#666] py-2 bg-[#f2f2f2]">Tap on the picture</p>
          </div>
          <div class="text-2xl text-[#aaa] self-center">→</div>
          <div class="flex-1 rounded-[15px] overflow-hidden shadow-lg mt-8">
            <img src={heroImages[3].src} alt="iOS – tap on the number icon" class="w-full h-auto object-cover" loading="lazy" />
            <p class="text-xs text-center text-[#666] py-2 bg-[#f2f2f2]">Tap on the number icon</p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- ── NDA NOTICE ── -->
    <section class="mx-5 sm:mx-10 lg:mx-[120px] my-4">
      <div class="bg-[#2c3e50] text-white rounded-2xl px-8 py-6 text-center">
        <p class="text-base lg:text-[18px] font-medium leading-relaxed">
          Due to the Non-Disclosure Agreement, I can't display complete research deck.
        </p>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- ── RESEARCH PHASE ── -->
    <section class="px-5 sm:px-10 lg:px-[120px] py-16 lg:py-20 bg-[#f9f9f9]">
      <div class="max-w-3xl mx-auto">
        <p class="text-primary font-bold text-[20px] mb-1">Research phase</p>
        <h2 class="font-bold text-[24px] lg:text-[28px] text-[#020202] mb-6">Collaborate with research team to identify the issues</h2>
        <p class="text-base lg:text-[20px] leading-relaxed text-[#020202] mb-6">
          Over the past two years, we collaborated with 2 researchers to conduct 10 research studies. These were key insights that we found:
        </p>
        <ul class="space-y-3">
          {researchInsights.map((insight) => (
            <li class="flex gap-3 text-base lg:text-[18px] text-[#020202] leading-relaxed">
              <span class="mt-1 shrink-0 w-2 h-2 rounded-full bg-primary"></span>
              <span>{insight}</span>
            </li>
          ))}
        </ul>
        <div class="mt-10 p-5 bg-white rounded-2xl border border-[#e5e5e5] shadow-sm">
          <p class="font-bold text-[#020202] text-base mb-2">Image number in the gallery</p>
          <p class="text-sm lg:text-base text-[#020202] leading-relaxed">
            Users understood that the number beneath the image gallery (e.g., 40+) indicated 40 additional photos would be available for viewing upon clicking.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- ── DISCOVERY PHASE ── -->
    <section class="px-5 sm:px-10 lg:px-[120px] py-16 lg:py-20">
      <div class="max-w-3xl mx-auto">
        <p class="text-primary font-bold text-[20px] mb-1">Discovery phase</p>
        <h2 class="font-bold text-[24px] lg:text-[28px] text-[#020202] mb-6">Competitive analysis of 58 apps and mobile browsers</h2>
        <p class="text-base lg:text-[20px] leading-relaxed text-[#020202] mb-4">We found that:</p>
        <ul class="space-y-3 mb-10">
          <li class="flex gap-3 text-base lg:text-[18px] text-[#020202] leading-relaxed">
            <span class="mt-1 shrink-0 w-2 h-2 rounded-full bg-primary"></span>
            <span>Most travel companies had similar native designs (common patterns) across all mobile devices.</span>
          </li>
          <li class="flex gap-3 text-base lg:text-[18px] text-[#020202] leading-relaxed">
            <span class="mt-1 shrink-0 w-2 h-2 rounded-full bg-primary"></span>
            <span>There were three gallery types that most companies used: mosaic, film strip view, and carousel.</span>
          </li>
        </ul>

        <h3 class="font-bold text-[20px] text-[#020202] mb-2">Analyze the competitor's features</h3>
        <p class="text-base text-[#020202] leading-relaxed mb-6">
          This is the full-screen mode from the examples.
        </p>

        <!-- Gallery type comparison -->
        <div class="grid grid-cols-3 gap-3 mb-10">
          {[
            { label: "Booking", type: "Mosaic" },
            { label: "Amazon", type: "Carousel" },
            { label: "Agoda", type: "Film strip" },
          ].map((item) => (
            <div class="bg-[#f2f2f2] rounded-xl overflow-hidden">
              <div class="bg-[#34495e] aspect-[9/14] flex flex-col items-center justify-center gap-2 p-4">
                <div class="w-full h-3 bg-white/20 rounded"></div>
                <div class="w-full h-3 bg-white/20 rounded"></div>
                <div class="w-3/4 h-3 bg-white/20 rounded self-start"></div>
              </div>
              <div class="p-3">
                <p class="text-xs font-bold text-[#020202]">{item.label}</p>
                <p class="text-xs text-[#666]">{item.type}</p>
              </div>
            </div>
          ))}
        </div>

        <p class="text-base text-[#020202] leading-relaxed mb-6">
          Many competitors implemented filter or sorting method. Here I curated the top three filter designs:
        </p>
        <div class="grid grid-cols-3 gap-3">
          {[
            { label: "Booking", type: "Two grid" },
            { label: "Agoda", type: "Mix grid" },
            { label: "Traveloka", type: "Single row" },
          ].map((item) => (
            <div class="bg-[#f2f2f2] rounded-xl overflow-hidden">
              <div class="bg-[#2c3e50] aspect-[9/14] flex flex-col items-center justify-center gap-2 p-4">
                <div class="w-full h-3 bg-white/20 rounded"></div>
                <div class="w-full h-3 bg-white/20 rounded"></div>
                <div class="w-3/4 h-3 bg-white/20 rounded self-start"></div>
              </div>
              <div class="p-3">
                <p class="text-xs font-bold text-[#020202]">{item.label}</p>
                <p class="text-xs text-[#666]">{item.type}</p>
              </div>
            </div>
          ))}
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- ── CONSISTENT DESIGN ── -->
    <section class="px-5 sm:px-10 lg:px-[120px] py-16 lg:py-20 bg-[#f9f9f9]">
      <div class="max-w-3xl mx-auto">
        <h2 class="font-bold text-[24px] lg:text-[28px] text-[#020202] mb-2">Create the consistent design</h2>
        <p class="text-primary font-semibold text-base mb-6">How did we create the same interaction pattern across all mobile devices?</p>

        <h3 class="font-bold text-[20px] text-[#020202] mb-2">Button consistency</h3>
        <p class="text-base text-[#020202] leading-relaxed mb-4">How did we create the button consistency across all mobile devices?</p>
        <div class="space-y-3 text-base text-[#020202] leading-relaxed">
          <p>iOS and Android show different button. Our goal was to maintain the button consistency across iOS and Android platforms.</p>
          <p>This carousel shows only 4 images. How could we convey to users that the carousel contains more than 4 images?</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- ── DESIGN PHASE – 3 VARIANTS ── -->
    <section class="px-5 sm:px-10 lg:px-[120px] py-16 lg:py-20">
      <div class="max-w-3xl mx-auto">
        <p class="text-primary font-bold text-[20px] mb-1">Design phase</p>
        <h2 class="font-bold text-[24px] lg:text-[28px] text-[#020202] mb-8">The video prototypes to test to the users</h2>
        <div class="space-y-10">
          {variants.map((v, i) => (
            <div class="flex flex-col sm:flex-row gap-6 items-start">
              <div class="shrink-0 rounded-[15px] overflow-hidden shadow-lg w-full sm:w-[160px]">
                <img
                  src={heroImages[i % heroImages.length].src}
                  alt={`${v.label} prototype`}
                  class="w-full h-auto object-cover"
                  loading="lazy"
                />
              </div>
              <div class="flex-1">
                <p class="font-bold text-primary text-base mb-2">{v.label}</p>
                <p class="text-base text-[#020202] leading-relaxed">{v.text}</p>
              </div>
            </div>
          ))}
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- ── PDP GALLERY SECTIONS ── -->
    <section class="px-5 sm:px-10 lg:px-[120px] py-16 lg:py-20 bg-[#f9f9f9]">
      <div class="max-w-3xl mx-auto space-y-12">

        <div>
          <h2 class="font-bold text-[24px] lg:text-[28px] text-[#020202] mb-4">PDP Gallery View</h2>
          <div class="space-y-3 text-base text-[#020202] leading-relaxed">
            <p>In both V1 and V2, the icons performed effectively, with users encountering no issues. While V1 directly signified the number of images available, V2 provided users with a preview of what they possibly see.</p>
            <p>Carousel dots worked perfectly with the swipe functionality. Users understood and knew how to navigate it. They could swipe the image left and right seamlessly without using an arrow.</p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div>
          <h2 class="font-bold text-[24px] lg:text-[28px] text-[#020202] mb-4">Full screen / lightbox view</h2>
          <div class="space-y-3 text-base text-[#020202] leading-relaxed">
            <p>What should the full-screen mode look like? How could we combine or optimize the design for both devices?</p>
            <p>This page has a swipe feature. However, the visual doesn't show that. How did we successfully communicate to travelers that the swipe feature exists?</p>
            <p>Having a description for each image is a perfect idea! But, the position might need some adjustment. What if we position it directly beneath the image?</p>
            <p>We implemented the rule of thirds as our guideline. According to the rule, we will get better compositions by positioning key elements along the gridlines.</p>
            <p>Although users understood that 1/25 means 25 pictures, the icon was not working. The icon didn't tell users it would direct them to the grid view.</p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div>
          <h2 class="font-bold text-[24px] lg:text-[28px] text-[#020202] mb-4">Grid view</h2>
          <div class="space-y-3 text-base text-[#020202] leading-relaxed">
            <p>V1 and V3 have the same number icon, giving users an idea of how many pictures are available. However, users ignored this. Question was: Should we keep this feature or remove it?</p>
            <p>Many users ignored this icon, though it can serve as a direction to the grid view in specific scenarios without going back to PDP.</p>
            <p>The phone-tilting idea worked in some ways. However, users didn't want to get more hassle by turning their phone to view the full-screen mode. While users disliked being compelled to tilt, they appreciated the concept when it was optional, as it allowed them to view larger images.</p>
            <p>V1, V2, and V3 navigation bars performed as intended. Users didn't show a distinct preference for either, as both seemed to meet their needs effectively. Given the results, we preferred to choose V2 or V3 option, as it aligned with EDGS pattern.</p>
          </div>
        </div>

      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- ── WHAT'S NEXT – PRODUCTION TEST ── -->
    <section class="px-5 sm:px-10 lg:px-[120px] py-16 lg:py-20">
      <div class="max-w-3xl mx-auto">
        <h2 class="font-bold text-[24px] lg:text-[28px] text-[#020202] mb-6">What's next step? Apply what we learned.</h2>

        <div class="grid sm:grid-cols-2 gap-6 mb-10">
          <div class="bg-[#f9f9f9] rounded-2xl overflow-hidden">
            <div class="flex gap-2 p-4">
              <div class="flex-1 rounded-xl overflow-hidden shadow-sm">
                <img src={heroImages[0].src} alt="Android thumbnail view" class="w-full h-auto object-cover" loading="lazy" />
              </div>
              <div class="flex-1 rounded-xl overflow-hidden shadow-sm">
                <img src={heroImages[1].src} alt="Android full gallery" class="w-full h-auto object-cover" loading="lazy" />
              </div>
            </div>
            <div class="px-4 pb-4">
              <p class="font-bold text-[#020202] text-sm mb-1">Production test control – Android</p>
              <p class="text-xs text-[#666]">Thumbnail view → Full gallery</p>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="bg-[#f9f9f9] rounded-2xl overflow-hidden">
            <div class="flex gap-2 p-4">
              <div class="flex-1 rounded-xl overflow-hidden shadow-sm">
                <img src={heroImages[2].src} alt="iOS current experience" class="w-full h-auto object-cover" loading="lazy" />
              </div>
              <div class="flex-1 rounded-xl overflow-hidden shadow-sm">
                <img src={heroImages[3].src} alt="iOS tap picture" class="w-full h-auto object-cover" loading="lazy" />
              </div>
            </div>
            <div class="px-4 pb-4">
              <p class="font-bold text-[#020202] text-sm mb-1">Production test control – iOS</p>
              <p class="text-xs text-[#666]">Current experience → Tap on the picture</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <h3 class="font-bold text-[20px] text-[#020202] mb-4">Result – User flows V1, V2, and V3 interactions</h3>
        <p class="text-base text-[#020202] leading-relaxed mb-6">
          There wasn't much interaction in the full screen view. However, users could navigate the full screen feature with ease.
        </p>
        <p class="text-base text-[#020202] leading-relaxed">
          We chose this design pattern as users didn't often use a full screen feature as we expected. The second important thing is grid view after the PDP native gallery. With that, we created a single tap to lead users to grid view, displaying more images.
        </p>

        <div class="mt-8">
          <h3 class="font-bold text-[20px] text-[#020202] mb-4">What's next for list and grid view? Apply what we learned.</h3>
          <div class="grid sm:grid-cols-2 gap-4 mb-6">
            <div class="bg-[#f2f2f2] rounded-xl p-5">
              <p class="font-bold text-primary mb-1 text-sm">OPTION 1 – Number icon</p>
              <p class="text-sm text-[#020202] leading-relaxed">The advantage of this is that travelers will know that 25 images will appear after clicking this button.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="bg-[#f2f2f2] rounded-xl p-5">
              <p class="font-bold text-primary mb-1 text-sm">OPTION 2 – Grid view icon</p>
              <p class="text-sm text-[#020202] leading-relaxed">The advantage of this is that this icon will direct users to gallery view directly as this icon is more commonly being used.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="space-y-3 text-base text-[#020202] leading-relaxed">
            <p>We used grid icon in the list view to display the grid view gallery.</p>
            <p><strong>List view:</strong> Provides larger and more detailed view of images. Includes description for each image.</p>
            <p><strong>Grid view:</strong> Enables users to scroll faster and at the same, skim through images.</p>
            <p>We replaced the carousel dot with a picture count icon. Despite this change, users still understood that the gallery can be swiped (for both portrait and landscape views).</p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- ── FINAL RESULT ── -->
    <section class="px-5 sm:px-10 lg:px-[120px] py-16 lg:py-24 bg-[#f2f2f2]">
      <div class="max-w-3xl mx-auto text-center">
        <h2 class="font-bold text-[24px] lg:text-[28px] text-[#020202] mb-8">Final Result</h2>
        <div class="inline-block bg-white rounded-2xl px-12 py-10 shadow-md mb-8">
          <p class="text-5xl lg:text-6xl font-bold text-primary mb-2">+8%</p>
